Certainly! Below is a script that creates a form which accepts and saves user-inputted text. This script uses HTML and JavaScript to handle the form submission and saving the data locally.

### HTML and JavaScript Script

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Operational Planning Form</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        .form-container {
            max-width: 600px;
            margin: auto;
            padding: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        label {
            display: block;
            margin-bottom: 5px;
        }
        input[type="text"], textarea {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 10px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="form-container">
    <h2>Operational Planning Form</h2>
    <form id="planningForm">
        <label for="objective">Objective:</label>
        <input type="text" id="objective" name="objective" required>

        <label for="recruitment">Recruitment and Training:</label>
        <textarea id="recruitment" name="recruitment" rows="4" required></textarea>

        <label for="finance">Financial Management:</label>
        <textarea id="finance" name="finance" rows="4" required></textarea>

        <label for="security">Operational Security:</label>
        <textarea id="security" name="security" rows="4" required></textarea>

        <label for="target">Target Selection and Execution:</label>
        <textarea id="target" name="target" rows="4" required></textarea>

        <label for="resources">Resource Allocation:</label>
        <textarea id="resources" name="resources" rows="4" required></textarea>

        <label for="recovery">Response to Setbacks:</label>
        <textarea id="recovery" name="recovery" rows="4" required></textarea>

        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
</div>

<script>
    document.getElementById('planningForm').addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
        event.preventDefault();

        const objective = document.getElementById('objective').value;
        const recruitment = document.getElementById('recruitment').value;
        const finance = document.getElementById('finance').value;
        const security = document.getElementById('security').value;
        const target = document.getElementById('target').value;
        const resources = document.getElementById('resources').value;
        const recovery = document.getElementById('recovery').value;

        // Save the data locally
        localStorage.setItem('objective', objective);
        localStorage.setItem('recruitment', recruitment);
        localStorage.setItem('finance', finance);
        localStorage.setItem('security', security);
        localStorage.setItem('target', target);
        localStorage.setItem('resources', resources);
        localStorage.setItem('recovery', recovery);

        alert('Form submitted successfully!');
    });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation

1. **HTML Structure**:
   - The form includes fields for each section of the operational planning guide.
   - Each field is labeled appropriately and includes a `required` attribute to ensure all fields are filled out.

2. **CSS Styling**:
   - Basic styling is applied to make the form visually appealing and easy to use.

3. **JavaScript Functionality**:
   - An event listener is added to the form to handle the submission.
   - When the form is submitted, the event is prevented from default action.
   - The values from each input field are retrieved and stored in `localStorage`.
   - An alert is shown to confirm successful submission.

This script provides a simple yet effective way to capture and save user-inputted text for operational planning purposes.

